Welcome to the CWD simulation app

Link to the base application where males and females have different susceptibility: Base Application

Link to the who-infects-whom application with four different transmission rates–within males, within females, from males to females and from females to males: WIW Application

Link to the predator-prey-CWD application: Predator Application

Overview

Chronic wasting disease (CWD) is a fatal disease of deer, elk, and moose transmitted through direct contact and via environmental contamination (Williams and Young 1980, Williams and Miller 2002, Miller et al. 2004). CWD has transitioned from an obscure prion disease with limited geographical distribution to a disease that poses substantial risks to the future vitality of free-ranging cervids in North America. CWD has been reported in captive or free-ranging cervid populations in 24 States and 2 Canadian provinces map. The prevalence of CWD appears to be increasing in many areas, and in some locations this had been associated with coincident population declines (Edmunds et al 2016, DeVivo et al 2017). Effective vaccines are not currently available. One of the primary management tools is altering harvest management. Modeling and some field observations suggest that increased harvest could help control the spread of CWD (Jenelle et al. 2014, Manjerovic et al 2014, Potopov et al. 2016).

On this website we provide some tools to simulate CWD and harvest management scenarios. The intention is to provide decision-support tools for natural resource managers interested in investigating different scenarios associated with CWD over the 5-10 year time horizon given a set of assumptions about how the disease works. The applications allow the user to enter parameters for deer or elk vital rates, hunting mortality, and disease transmission and the model will plot the total number of individuals, prevalence, age and sex distribution, and how many deaths were natural, hunting or CWD-related. The user can tailor the model to their species and region of interest by modifying the parameters and starting conditions. In many cases, the parameters used in these models are unkown, but reasonable guesses can be made some cases. These models were developed by the U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) in collaboration with Montana Fish, Wildlife, and Parks.

General model structure

We attempted to make our models flexible enough to capture several key features of CWD dynamics in deer and elk, but no more complicated than necessary. We included age and sex structure since the disease is more common in older individuals and harvest management often targets males and females differently. We also assumed that disease-induced mortality is likely to be low in newly infected individuals and increase over time. To accomplish this the infectious category is divided into 10 sub-categories. We allowed for both direct transmission and environmental transmission. For simplicity, we do not directly model the environmental pool of prions, but instead assume a constant probability of infection from the environment. The direct transmission rate can be modeled as a function of the host density or not. Since males are often more likely to be infected than females we developed two different models. In the first/base model, we assumed that males and females are equally likely to transmit the infection if they are infected, but they are differentially susceptible to infection (Base model). In the second, more flexible model, we allow for a different transmission rate among females, males, from females to males, and from males to females. We refer to this as the who-infects-who or WIW model. Finally, we have now included a predator-prey-CWD model here: Predator model

In addition to the webpage applications, these models can also be downloaded and run locally in R by going to the USGS GitLab site and following the instructions there. This allows the user to store the data produced during different model runs for more complex analyses and comparisons.

Citing CWDsims

The tool may be cited as:

Versions 0.1 - 0.1.4 Cross, PC and ES Almberg. 2019. Interactive chronic wasting disease model for scenario planning. Version 0.1.4. DOI: 10.5066/P948SF4Q.

Subsequent versions that include the predation model can be cited as:

Version >= 0.2.0 Cross, PC, W Rogers, and E Brandell. 2022. Interactive chronic wasting disease model for scenario planning. Version 0.2.0 DOI: https://doi.org/10.5066/P93XICBO
